    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "my realtor just mentioned escrow and said it's part of the closing process. i'm a first time buyer so i'm a bit lost lol. what actually is escrow and why do i need it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow, in the context of buying a home, is essentially a neutral third party holding the funds and documents until all the conditions of the sale are met. Think of it like a very careful, highly organized middleman, which is a lot less chaotic than trying to manage a massive, multi-faceted transaction yourself. You need it because it protects both you, the buyer, and the seller, ensuring that the money doesn't go to the seller until you've officially received the keys and the title is clear, and vice versa. It's a safety net that keeps the whole process from descending into a messy, unpredictable scramble of misplaced paperwork and nervous energy.",
      "source": "target",
