    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so like, who actually holds the money? is it the lawyer or a bank? and like, what happens if there's a dispute over something that's supposed to be in escrow?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Who holds the money in escrow depends on the local real estate customs, but it's usually a dedicated escrow company or sometimes a title company, rather than just your lawyer or the bank directly. These entities are legally bound to hold the funds in a separate, protected account. If a dispute arises—say, over a repair that the seller promised to fix before closing—the escrow agent acts as the referee, holding the funds hostage until the disagreement is resolved according to the contract. They won't release the money to either party until the agreed-upon conditions are satisfied.",
      "source": "target",
